WEBVTT

00:00:00.960 --> 00:00:06.880
So thank you so much for having me. I'm located in Halifax, Nova Scotia, where it's

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:16.320
quite beautiful here today. And what I'm going to sort of talk about is about security and how to

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:25.840
kind of like approach building, like getting your data scientist to work on data in a secure

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:30.400
environment interfacing with those other parts of the company. And one of the sort of things I

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:36.160
was thinking about while I was sort of trying to figure out what to say about this is that there's

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:43.840
not really a kind of right answer in terms of what level of security you need for any of these

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:49.360
systems. So these are kind of like general strategies, very general strategy, I think

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:53.599
the particular things you need to do, like, we need this kind of authentication, or the data

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:59.680
needs to be stored in this way or tracked in some fashion, are going to be individual to

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.120
the place that you work. So this is kind of more about like, how do you work with the people

00:01:05.120 --> 00:01:09.120
and systems at your company? And how do you set those things up to be successful?

00:01:09.919 --> 00:01:26.400
So this is my lovely stove picture. And things over. So a little bit about Socure. So Socure

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:33.519
is an identity company. So we build basically models and data products that help people

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:38.160
identify fraudsters. So whenever you apply for like a bank or a credit card,

00:01:39.919 --> 00:01:45.599
you, your bank sends your information to either a company like ours, or another model,

00:01:45.599 --> 00:01:50.160
or another or an internal model to sort of check like, are you really who you say you are? This is

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:56.480
for regulatory reasons to make sure that people aren't like wandering money. It's also for just

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:00.559
loss prevention, like fraud costs companies a lot of money. So they try to do things that

00:02:00.800 --> 00:02:08.880
produce that that reduce fraud. And, and we're the best at that. So we have some of the best

00:02:08.880 --> 00:02:14.960
products in these markets. And a lot of that has to do with the fact that we've kind of from the

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:21.759
start, set up systems where we're able to confidently work with very, very sensitive data

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:25.360
of various different kinds and segregate data that's more sensitive from data that's less

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:31.759
sensitive. And using those kind of data assets, we're able to build these kind of

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:40.000
pretty wonderful models. We're also going through a period of very, very fast growth.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:46.880
So we're a revenue is basically growing, but depending on how you count revenue,

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:53.119
one and 200% year over year, we started the year 120 people are probably going to be growing to

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:59.679
about 500 people at the end of this year. So we're hiring. If you're, if you are interested

00:02:59.679 --> 00:03:06.960
in this area, it's it's rewarding, and a wonderful place to work. And so this is put all this puts a

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:13.759
lot of pressure on security. And because the kind of ways you have to think about security,

00:03:13.759 --> 00:03:18.960
when you're growing this fast, are slightly different from the ways that you can think

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:25.279
about security at a larger company, just because, you know, if you sort of imagine, like, so I

00:03:25.279 --> 00:03:30.160
started at secure two years ago, and I'm one of the more senior people there, right? So all the people

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:34.320
who joined after me have like less context about, you know, why do we have things set up this way?

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:39.679
What are the risks? What's the threat model, all those different things. But I found it really

00:03:39.679 --> 00:03:45.839
helpful environment to sort of learn this stuff. Because I think if you can kind of build secure

00:03:45.839 --> 00:03:52.080
systems at these sort of like, fast growing company places, it really helps to think about

00:03:52.080 --> 00:03:58.240
how to make them work at all different types of companies. But so that's just a little bit of

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:05.360
context. So I want to sort of talk about what I sort of think of as the bad place, the security

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:11.520
bad place that a lot of places find themselves in. And this is kind of the basic conflict between data

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:18.000
scientists, and really everybody else. But you can see a similar conflict occurs between like,

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.000
you know, salespeople and security people, some degree like engineers and security people,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.880
but definitely data scientists and security people, it's the worst. And the basic conflict

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:33.119
is that the safest way to deal with sensitive data is to just delete it, right? To not use it,

00:04:33.119 --> 00:04:36.480
if you can't delete it, you want to make sure that you don't give anybody access to it.

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:40.160
And if you can't give, you can't prevent people from accessing it all, you want to have like a

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:44.720
small number of people. And it has to be really, really annoying to access, right? So other kind of

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:49.440
like the from a security perspective, that's a hierarchy of data safety, right? And as soon as

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:54.079
you have somebody who's actually like, I'm going to go open up a data set and look at, you know,

00:04:54.079 --> 00:05:01.600
the emails or look at the name. That's a kind of like security nightmare for people. But from a

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:06.239
data science perspective, like there's a lot of insight that you're getting from that data that

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:12.720
you actually do need to look at the data. So for example, if we have like fraud, fraudster,

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:18.320
a fraud ring coming in, they might have like a particular email pattern, which we don't know

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:23.679
about until you actually kind of look at that, those, those, those scores, you look at them and

00:05:23.679 --> 00:05:28.799
say, like, okay, like, what are the emails that are, you know, causing us to decide this person

00:05:28.799 --> 00:05:33.359
is fraudulent? Like, you know, how does what does that make sense? At some point, you maybe can build

00:05:33.359 --> 00:05:38.239
an automated system to detect that pattern. But at some point, data scientists do need to actually

00:05:38.239 --> 00:05:44.880
like be able to look at the data in some environment, right? So what I've noticed

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:52.239
that happens with security is security groups, I'm just going to refer to that as security,

00:05:52.239 --> 00:05:56.480
like, so this is maybe like compliance people, security engineers, you know, the people who are

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:02.160
there to try to make sure that your company doesn't get hacked. And you know, your employees

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:08.480
don't leave, you know, their laptops at, you know, at coffee shops with precious information on them.

00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:14.799
You know, so security, like, they'll come into a situation, and they'll try to fix something

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:19.040
that's broken. That's an old system that was set up some way that, you know, maybe

00:06:19.679 --> 00:06:24.320
it was good at the time, or maybe it was just never thought about, but it's some battle system.

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:29.440
And they'll say, like, look, this is a big, you know, problem, right? Like,

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:33.519
this could be an attack here, we got to fix this, right? But in order to fix, they have to

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:40.880
direct money from new projects to fix the old ones. And usually, like, in most companies, like,

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:46.559
the groups that are responsible for security don't actually have the power to direct resources like

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:51.600
that. And so they have to sort of try to have this fight between like the value that these new

00:06:52.239 --> 00:06:57.119
things will do versus fixing the old ones. And oftentimes, they don't get their way and

00:06:57.119 --> 00:07:03.200
that old fix doesn't happen. But the power that security does always have is the power to veto

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:07.440
new things, right? So when a new project comes in, it usually goes through a security review,

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:12.239
and if it fails, it doesn't get put in place, right? So you have this situation where, like,

00:07:12.239 --> 00:07:18.160
the company can't fix the old security problems, but then can also put in new systems in place

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:23.679
because they get vetoed, right? And this is kind of like on some level, like, the second,

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:27.839
the third one is sort of like, partially, I think, an emotional reaction to the second one,

00:07:27.839 --> 00:07:32.640
like people didn't feel heard about the big problems. So they maybe like enforce those

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:39.279
policies, like too strictly for some new systems. Everybody thinks that the other side is unreasonable,

00:07:39.279 --> 00:07:44.320
like, so the data scientists feel like security is just putting roadblocks, like needless roadblocks

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:48.160
in their place. And they're like, this is way safer than the old thing that we were doing. So

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:54.399
why not do this new one? Security thinks that the rest of the business doesn't care about security.

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:01.200
And then everybody just stops talking. So I think this is really common. And it's worth knowing that

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:07.119
even if this isn't like a real problem at your business, most of the people who are coming into

00:08:07.119 --> 00:08:11.200
that business have had experiences at other companies that are like this. So like most,

00:08:11.200 --> 00:08:15.359
pretty much all the security people I know, have had situations where they were like, I was at this

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:21.760
other job. And there was this like, giant, you know, giant fire of a bad system that never got

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:25.760
fixed. And it was so frustrating. And I left, right. So they're kind of carrying that from

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:31.920
from job to job. And data scientists often feel like we can do, we've had all these experiences

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:36.080
where it's like, I could do so much, produce so much value, but I just can't get access to the

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:43.599
data that I need to actually produce that value. So that's the bad place. So this is a really big

00:08:43.599 --> 00:08:48.400
problem, because it's sort of all of the friction of a high security environment with none of the

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:55.440
security. Because all of these kinds of hacks or security issues, they're adversarial, usually,

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:00.400
so somebody is looking for the weak link in your company's armor. And it really doesn't matter

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:06.719
if you have a 40% of your systems are secure, or 90% of your systems are secure, because they

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:12.559
will tend to find the holes, right? So that so you kind of want to always focus your energy on like

00:09:12.559 --> 00:09:17.119
lifting the floor of your business rather than having like some small number of things that are

00:09:17.119 --> 00:09:23.440
like super duper secure. The analogy that I kind of use for this is like, if all of your windows

00:09:23.440 --> 00:09:27.840
in your house are open, you know, it doesn't really matter if you walk the door, right? Like

00:09:27.840 --> 00:09:34.000
that somebody a burglar is going to like just go through the window. And so you get this sort of

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.559
system where you're like, you've put in a lot of friction, like a lot of fights, your business

00:09:38.559 --> 00:09:42.719
can't move very quickly, but you haven't really gained that much in terms of security overall,

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:50.559
overall. So as a data scientist, you can help with this problem by kind of trying to understand and

00:09:50.559 --> 00:09:56.000
like being intentional about being an ally to the security parts of your organization.

00:09:57.039 --> 00:10:03.039
Because oftentimes, when you're when I like decision makers are hearing security issues from

00:10:03.039 --> 00:10:06.559
several different places in the company, they're much more likely to be fixed. So if it's not just

00:10:06.559 --> 00:10:11.039
coming from the people who are kind of always bringing up security issues, you know, like if

00:10:11.039 --> 00:10:15.280
it's coming from somebody else as well, like that's a really powerful way of making progress on these

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:21.039
things. And the something that's helped me think about this is just to sort of like think about

00:10:21.039 --> 00:10:27.760
the mindset of somebody who is whose job it is to identify low probability risks at a business,

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:31.599
right? And so this is kind of they live in this like lonely, anxious world, like they're often

00:10:32.159 --> 00:10:35.840
saying no to awesome stuff. Everybody else is like, this would be so awesome. And then the

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:40.719
security person is like, No, we're not doing that. That would be awful. And there's also just

00:10:40.719 --> 00:10:44.799
this a lot of anxiety, right? Like they don't get any positive feedback, right? It's like nothing

00:10:44.799 --> 00:10:49.760
happens. It's not because they're like, Oh, this is I did such a great job, right? It's just like,

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:54.159
there's I'm just constantly worried about these small, low probability things that will happen

00:10:54.159 --> 00:10:58.559
that all have missed that will sink the business, right? So it's a really like, high anxiety

00:10:59.119 --> 00:11:06.080
workplace. So it's kind of like, understanding that and, and, like, putting yourself in that

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:10.799
mindset when you're talking to people in security is really helpful. Because you can kind of sort of

00:11:10.799 --> 00:11:15.679
like, talk about like, you know, like, basically just sort of like, not think of that they're

00:11:15.679 --> 00:11:20.080
being ridiculous, right? Like, it's often something where it's like, the thing that seems to you as

00:11:20.080 --> 00:11:25.359
being like overly strict is often because like, when you're spending your time thinking about

00:11:25.359 --> 00:11:32.080
these, you know, things that happen 100 times, but that are really tragic. It's, you're sort of

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:38.559
more likely to find those things and think that they're important. And another good thing to do

00:11:38.559 --> 00:11:43.520
is just to talk about security projects. So pretty much everywhere that I've worked,

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:49.679
there's a list of things where it's just like, you know, these are important security projects

00:11:49.679 --> 00:11:54.640
that we have not done, because for whatever reason, they just haven't gotten, you know,

00:11:54.640 --> 00:11:58.719
gotten to the top of the pile. Because there's always new things going on the top of the pile,

00:11:58.719 --> 00:12:04.000
and they kind of get worse and worse over time. So being somebody who's kind of just like, not

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.799
part of that security organization, but is just like aware of those issues and continues to bring

00:12:08.799 --> 00:12:15.440
them up over and over and over again, helps the rest of the like, compliance security teams

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:21.039
sort of realize that you're on their side when you're talking about building any of these systems.

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:30.320
And then do things like sort of have one on ones with people just sort of talk to them about

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:34.320
like their job, what they're what they're working on, develop those things. And then the last one,

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:38.080
which I think is really important is that prove that you can make progress on these things,

00:12:38.080 --> 00:12:43.440
like so that prove, prove to security, that you have a data scientist who's handling this stuff,

00:12:43.440 --> 00:12:47.280
can push these things through and accomplish them, you can start with small little things

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:52.719
that are like security, bad practices on the data science team, like improving those a little bit

00:12:52.719 --> 00:12:57.200
and being able to demonstrate that is really important. Why is that important? It's important,

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:03.840
because when you're setting up a system, it allows you to make promises to security and

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:08.400
compliance groups, and have them believe you. So you can say, like, we're putting this in place

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:11.679
now, because it's better than what we had before, here are the three or four things we'd like to

00:13:11.679 --> 00:13:17.280
improve over the next six months. And if you don't do this, where you kind of like demonstrate over

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:21.760
and over again that you're going to like move that security ball forward, they're going to say

00:13:21.760 --> 00:13:25.679
no, like, we have to do everything that we all the requirements today on day one.

00:13:26.799 --> 00:13:29.840
Because I don't trust that you're going to actually do what you say you're going to do in

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:37.679
terms of of delivering on these patches, basically. So if you kind of do all that, like, and sort of

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:41.760
start thinking of yourself, and maybe this is like a whole data science team, or maybe it's like a

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:46.640
couple of people on that team. So at SoCure, this is something that I've done, basically as kind of

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:51.200
like a liaison between the big group of data scientists and the big group of security people.

00:13:51.200 --> 00:13:57.280
So now, basically, like those groups don't feel like they need to talk to each other as much,

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:01.919
like they both can talk to me and my team. And we can sort of translate and be like, you know,

00:14:01.919 --> 00:14:05.760
like, have the context of what the data scientists are trying to do, have this context of what the

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:11.280
security people are trying to do, and be able to, like, find the sort of solution that kind of like

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:17.679
works for both groups. But once you kind of do that, it sort of unlocks a lot of the rest of it.

00:14:17.679 --> 00:14:23.359
But if you can't get out of that bad place, you're not going to be able to develop things

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:26.400
that are very secure, in my experience, you're also not going to be able to develop things that

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:33.119
are amenable to really productive data science work. So this is like, I know, this is a little

00:14:33.119 --> 00:14:37.119
funny, spend 10 minutes to talk about, like, you should be friends with your co workers,

00:14:37.119 --> 00:14:46.239
but I work in a tech company. So it's important to do that. Okay, so the thing once you kind of

00:14:46.239 --> 00:14:52.799
have that relationship, like, I think it's important to come up with just a list, like an

00:14:52.799 --> 00:15:00.400
ordered list of security priorities as they relate to data science. And this is, it's important to do

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:05.599
that. And to kind of like, think about this as a, like, just to speak in a real basic language,

00:15:05.599 --> 00:15:09.280
because a lot of times, like, people who work in security don't really have a good sense of like,

00:15:09.919 --> 00:15:15.359
what it is that data scientists do. And like, what, like, what do you do day to day, right?

00:15:15.359 --> 00:15:19.119
Like the programming that data scientists do is very different from the programming that you would

00:15:19.119 --> 00:15:24.719
do as a, like an application software engineer. It's much more like a process of discovery than

00:15:24.719 --> 00:15:30.239
it is a process of implementation, a lot of those different things. And then these two things that I

00:15:30.239 --> 00:15:35.760
would really highlight are to precisely articulate the business value of the data science work.

00:15:36.640 --> 00:15:41.760
And this is, at SoCure, like, this is kind of easy on one level, because, you know, we're a

00:15:41.760 --> 00:15:48.080
data science company, all we sell are statistical models, basically. So there's, we can sort of say,

00:15:48.080 --> 00:15:52.559
in general, like, you know, our work is valuable to the company, it's the main product that we sell.

00:15:52.559 --> 00:16:00.239
But being really precise about it helps to narrow down, like, what kind of data access you need. So

00:16:00.239 --> 00:16:03.280
when you're more precise about the business value that you're producing, you might, you might sort

00:16:03.280 --> 00:16:09.039
of say, like, okay, well, actually, like, I can get that same business value with, you know,

00:16:09.039 --> 00:16:15.119
10% of the people, only 10% of the people having access to this sensitive data, or I can get that

00:16:15.119 --> 00:16:21.440
same business value with the same sort of, like, productive velocity, if I'm, you know, using,

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:25.599
like, this kind of environment versus this other one. But being really, really sort of,

00:16:26.559 --> 00:16:33.679
like, specific about, like, why do you need to access this data? Like, why does it, like,

00:16:33.679 --> 00:16:38.400
why do you need to do that? What's the value that that particular piece of access provides to the

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:43.359
to the company, helps you sort of narrow things down, and also, like, convince people that

00:16:43.359 --> 00:16:47.119
that access is worthwhile, right? If you can sort of say, like, look, here's the business value that

00:16:47.119 --> 00:16:54.799
this access grants us, you're going to have a lot better time getting that access. An example of

00:16:54.799 --> 00:17:00.880
this is sort of say you have, like, a database that has intermingled data that's, like, sensitive

00:17:00.880 --> 00:17:05.839
and not sensitive, and most of your business value might be accessing the non-sensitive data. But

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:11.040
since you only have the one database account, right, like, you can, you kind of, by accessing

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:17.520
the non-sensitive data, you might also be exposing the sensitive data. So that's an example of

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:21.280
something where you're, like, okay, if we, like, split that data apart, you know, so that we put

00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:28.160
the sensitive data in a whole other place, you're able to be more, like, just even, like, you're,

00:17:28.160 --> 00:17:32.959
the data scientists are doing the same amount of work, same positive stuff, they're just, like,

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:38.640
the collateral access is lower. Similarly, from the security side, get them to purchase, precisely

00:17:38.640 --> 00:17:42.400
articulate the threat model that they're worried about. And this kind of goes back to that sort of,

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:46.560
like, vague anxiety that people have, which is, like, you just have this vague anxiety of stuff,

00:17:46.560 --> 00:17:49.359
and then you just veto things, because you're just, like, I'm just anxious, I don't want,

00:17:49.359 --> 00:17:54.800
I don't want any kind of breach. But when you sort of are, like, more intentional about, like,

00:17:54.800 --> 00:18:01.119
what kinds of attacks are we trying to prevent, you have a better chance of kind of, like, right-sizing

00:18:01.119 --> 00:18:08.800
the security access. So an example of this is, like, you know, you might worry about mistake

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:12.560
from your company, like, you don't want your employees making a mistake and putting a file

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:16.400
in some place that they shouldn't be putting it. Or you might worry that they're malicious,

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:20.640
that your employees are actually going to try to steal this data from you and sell it to somebody

00:18:20.640 --> 00:18:26.640
else, right? Those are very, very different threat models. And if you, and the systems that you're

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:29.760
going to design that are going to be good for the first one are not going to be good for the second

00:18:29.760 --> 00:18:37.119
one. And oftentimes, like, when security groups will have, like, some internal version of that,

00:18:37.119 --> 00:18:40.640
but getting them to tell you that so that in a way that you can understand and communicate to

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:45.760
the rest of the people who work with you is going to help you get buy-in from data scientists to

00:18:45.760 --> 00:18:49.839
use those systems, and also just sometimes give you an opportunity to kind of argue back a little

00:18:49.839 --> 00:18:56.160
bit about what you really need to do. And then the sort of goal of this is just, like, an ordered

00:18:56.160 --> 00:19:00.400
list of, like, these are the big security problems that we have, and we're going to try to go down

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:05.439
this list from top to bottom and fix them. And you might be in terms of priority, you might also

00:19:05.439 --> 00:19:10.719
include some things like how easy are these things to do or not. But coming up with this thing where

00:19:10.719 --> 00:19:15.040
everybody's agreeing these are the main things, and then that's where we're going to try to put

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:20.880
our energy towards to raise the floor for your security thing rather than trying to fix the

00:19:20.880 --> 00:19:28.319
new ones is really helpful. Okay, so that's all kind of like prologue. These are my three principles

00:19:28.319 --> 00:19:35.359
for building secure systems. One is childproof rooms. Second one is developer experience is a

00:19:35.359 --> 00:19:41.680
security problem. And third one is to buy things and not build them. Let's talk about childproof

00:19:41.680 --> 00:19:47.439
rooms. This is my daughter's playroom. And this is kind of, like, I feel like the perfect analogy

00:19:47.439 --> 00:19:52.479
for what you want to do with data scientists, especially new data scientists who are just

00:19:52.479 --> 00:19:58.800
joining your company. You want to give them a place that has all of their stuff that is really

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:04.560
nice, and that they can't, like, burn your house down, right? And so it's a place where you can,

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:09.760
like, just say, like, go play, you know, like, go do your thing in here. And I will make sure I will

00:20:09.760 --> 00:20:15.359
do the work to make sure that this room as a whole is safe, so I can, like, you know, go cook

00:20:15.359 --> 00:20:19.599
dinner or something like that. But all your books are in here, all your toys are in here, you know,

00:20:19.599 --> 00:20:26.880
it's got all the CPU and RAM that you need, you know, and you can sort of go nuts. So they're

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:32.400
really, like, places where people can't hurt the company. And this is the only way that you can

00:20:32.400 --> 00:20:38.560
onboard people quickly and have it be safe, because there's no way that a new employee

00:20:38.560 --> 00:20:45.599
in their first month of work is going to be able to understand, like, the security and regulatory

00:20:45.599 --> 00:20:49.599
environments that SoCure operates in. Like, the only way that we're going to be able to get them

00:20:49.599 --> 00:20:54.959
to abide by those policies is if we kind of make the situation, the environment that they're in,

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:02.079
enforce those policies. So this kind of means that when you embed, put those secure things

00:21:02.079 --> 00:21:07.920
inside the system that you're building, you don't have to tell people about it as much,

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:10.800
right? Because it's just, like, that's just what it is. You don't tell people that the,

00:21:11.439 --> 00:21:15.680
you know, like, that, like, it's kind of like, I don't know, whenever you go into, like, a really

00:21:15.680 --> 00:21:20.400
well designed, like, hospital or something like that, like, how you use these various different

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:24.160
things is obvious, like, there's only one natural way of doing it. And that's kind of what you're

00:21:24.160 --> 00:21:27.839
going for. You don't want to have a situation where you're basically, like, having people read

00:21:27.839 --> 00:21:33.839
100 page policy documents and expecting that they're gonna abide by them. Nobody can do that.

00:21:33.839 --> 00:21:37.199
And definitely new people can't. So if you're, like, so if you think about, like, our stuff,

00:21:37.199 --> 00:21:41.040
like, we're going to be, if we have, like, 100 people starting in the next three months,

00:21:42.239 --> 00:21:46.959
we're not going to be able to teach them how security works, like, we're going to be able to

00:21:46.959 --> 00:21:50.719
build a system such that they can just drop in there and work and it is secure,

00:21:50.719 --> 00:21:56.959
we're confident about that. But, but there's no way for it to, there's no way to do this without,

00:21:56.959 --> 00:22:03.280
like, having this thing be kind of like, childproof, you know, like, it's not, it's something

00:22:03.280 --> 00:22:07.439
where they don't need to be a grown up person at a company, they can just go for it as a toddler.

00:22:09.920 --> 00:22:17.280
So the next one is this idea of that developer experience as a core security problem. And so

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:23.199
this is something that I think is not well understood by people who work in security

00:22:23.199 --> 00:22:29.760
in their day to day. Because people who work in security come from a model where it's just like,

00:22:29.760 --> 00:22:35.839
it's kind of like a police model or a legal model, where it's like, I'll just say what the law is,

00:22:36.479 --> 00:22:40.160
right? Like, I'll put some policy out, I'll say what the law is, and then everybody's just going

00:22:40.160 --> 00:22:45.599
to do that. Right? And like, we have, like, you know, we have really smart, thoughtful employees,

00:22:45.599 --> 00:22:49.280
like, they understand that they're supposed to be following the rules. So like, they'll just,

00:22:49.280 --> 00:22:52.640
they'll just do what I what we tell them to do. And there'll be some email that goes out,

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:56.239
everybody will read that email, everybody will understand it, everybody will be able to apply

00:22:56.239 --> 00:23:00.800
it to their experience. And, you know, like, they'll just do the right thing.

00:23:02.800 --> 00:23:07.760
But that's not exactly, that's not what happens. Because it turns out that like, you just don't

00:23:07.760 --> 00:23:14.239
have the enforcement mechanisms for those policies. So they're, once your company gets even

00:23:14.239 --> 00:23:21.040
a little bit big, you're not able to really audit what exactly everybody is doing. And all of the

00:23:21.040 --> 00:23:24.959
people who you've hired are like, you've hired them because they're like really clever with computers.

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:31.680
And people who are who are really clever with computers can like sort of subtly circumvent

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:35.359
things that they even if they might not know that they're not supposed to be doing something,

00:23:35.359 --> 00:23:38.560
they might kind of know that they shouldn't do it. But it's like some really urgent project,

00:23:38.560 --> 00:23:42.400
and they've got to just get something out the door. Right? Like people will always sort of

00:23:42.400 --> 00:23:48.719
like end up taking some little shortcuts around, around something that they find burdensome,

00:23:48.719 --> 00:23:54.719
right? So if the thing that is secure, is also like a pain to use, difficult, unappealing,

00:23:55.760 --> 00:23:59.520
some people are going to not use it. And that's all you really need is like some people not using

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:04.319
a secure process. So you can either make it so that it's like it's impossible for them to do

00:24:04.319 --> 00:24:11.680
the wrong thing, like you've put up like big walls, or you can sort of understand their motivation,

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:16.880
which is that they want to get their work done as easily as possible. And so if you assume that

00:24:16.880 --> 00:24:21.119
they're going to do the easy thing, right, and you can make the right thing easy, then you can

00:24:22.079 --> 00:24:27.920
have some confidence that they're going to tend to do the right thing, right? Like, if you make it

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:33.760
like put up some roadblocks around make it super irritating to do some process that you think is

00:24:33.760 --> 00:24:37.839
insecure, and then also give them a really, really convenient way of doing this more secure process,

00:24:38.640 --> 00:24:43.520
you're going to have a lot of success with adoption. And I actually think from a security

00:24:43.520 --> 00:24:48.319
perspective, adoption is one of the big problems is just actually like getting people to do the

00:24:48.319 --> 00:24:54.000
thing. And and getting them to not like push back on it. So like, if you're trying to get something

00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.800
in place, you do often have to actually go through someone who is saying like, who is listening to

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:03.839
their their teammates to say, like, you know, is this actually going to be workable? If it's not

00:25:03.839 --> 00:25:08.079
workable, they'll kind of like escalate it and have some fight about whether they should put

00:25:08.079 --> 00:25:13.359
it in place. But if you kind of make it so that it's both easy and secure, you just avoid that

00:25:13.359 --> 00:25:18.479
whole conflict. And, and it makes the makes it a lot easier to get these things out the door.

00:25:23.439 --> 00:25:32.160
So the ways that I've used to build good developer experiences for, for secure projects,

00:25:32.160 --> 00:25:35.920
the first one, I think is really, really crucial is to control the client libraries.

