money off of our models and like the security stuff to make sure that we can develop those

00:36:27.439 --> 00:36:32.320
models safely and we don't have a breach. We don't like like for ethical and business reasons,

00:36:32.320 --> 00:36:37.199
we don't want to have that happen. That's a cost. It's an important cost. It's one we're happy to

00:36:37.199 --> 00:36:44.800
pay, but it's a cost. So every business or almost every business is going to go through rough times

00:36:44.800 --> 00:36:50.320
where they don't have enough cash flow. And in those times they were going to cut costs.

00:36:50.320 --> 00:36:54.719
They're going to neglect cost centers and they're going to put money into revenue centers. So the

00:36:54.719 --> 00:36:59.040
place that actually puts money on the balance sheet. And they'll do this even if it's in the

00:36:59.040 --> 00:37:04.159
long run, bad idea. Like even if it's a long run mistake to cut those cost centers, like cut those

00:37:04.159 --> 00:37:10.320
security people, cut those DevOps people. When you're kind of get in a threatening economic

00:37:10.320 --> 00:37:14.879
situation or threatening business situation, you just need to put revenue back on the business.

00:37:14.879 --> 00:37:19.360
You need to get it back into the black. So you'll tend to neglect cost centers.

00:37:20.399 --> 00:37:29.919
So while security is a cost for you, for the vendor, it is a revenue center. So if Databricks

00:37:29.919 --> 00:37:36.479
or Studio is thinking about like, should I invest in wrapping this brand new awesome security

00:37:36.479 --> 00:37:41.280
protocol? If they do that, there's going to be some customer out there who's going to buy their

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:48.639
product because they did that. So they're going to put money and stuff into that thing, even in

00:37:48.639 --> 00:37:53.280
times where their business is difficult. Because that's a big part of what the product is that

00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:56.959
they're selling. They're selling something that is secure, something that is compliant,

00:37:56.959 --> 00:38:02.959
something that works for all these companies that they're trying to sell to. So whenever you buy

00:38:02.959 --> 00:38:11.520
software or licensed software, you're basically moving security from living in your cost center

00:38:11.520 --> 00:38:16.159
world to being in the revenue center of your business. Because you're kind of like offshoring

00:38:16.159 --> 00:38:21.040
it to some degree. So a little bit, it's like a maintenance commitment to the future about we're

00:38:21.040 --> 00:38:24.479
going to keep this up to date. We're buying the software now, we're also committing to paying

00:38:24.479 --> 00:38:28.800
license fees for the next however long we use this thing. And that's kind of like putting a little bit

00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:37.360
of money every year into that system getting better and more secure. So this is really important

00:38:37.360 --> 00:38:41.840
also if you're growing, because as you're growing, your security requirements change.

00:38:41.840 --> 00:38:49.120
So when I was doing that review about how do we host

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:54.560
Shiny apps securely, that was in the security world of a small startup that might not make it.

00:38:55.040 --> 00:39:01.439
Now Secure is like we have a billion dollar valuation, we're in Forbes,

00:39:01.439 --> 00:39:05.600
we're a much, much bigger target than we were. So our security requirements have changed

00:39:05.600 --> 00:39:11.199
dramatically. The nice thing about buying software is that your vendor has other clients, has built

00:39:11.199 --> 00:39:15.679
these products for clients that have big company problems. So if you're a small company, you buy

00:39:15.679 --> 00:39:19.679
these things, you might look at it and be like, well, I don't need that, I don't need that,

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:24.879
I don't need that. But as you grow, suddenly you discover you need all of those things.

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:32.560
And then the thing about growth is that at some point you start being limited by people and not

00:39:32.560 --> 00:39:39.679
money. So it takes maybe six months or something to hire and onboard a new DevOps person,

00:39:40.719 --> 00:39:47.120
and we can't just hire 20 of them all at once. So right now, we're really

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:52.479
grateful for any opportunity where we can spend licensing money to avoid development work,

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:58.320
because we have tons of development work that is in our core business that there are no vendors

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:05.760
for. So anything that we can do where we're able to basically say, I'm going to put licensing money

00:40:05.760 --> 00:40:12.879
onto this problem helps us grow, because we can just basically just keep giving our vendor more

00:40:12.879 --> 00:40:19.120
cash for more licenses and support. And for the most part, the support works itself out,

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:24.399
relative to if we were trying to build these things ourselves.

00:40:26.320 --> 00:40:32.000
So our Studio Server or Studio Workbench is a good case study of this. So when we first

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:37.919
implemented this, it was for mostly remote R development. We were a pretty much universal R

00:40:37.919 --> 00:40:43.679
team on our stuff. So we wanted something where it was giving people more compute power, giving

00:40:43.679 --> 00:40:51.600
them a remote environment so that we knew that the data was location safe.

00:40:52.639 --> 00:40:56.560
And so it could be controlled and audited, and you can shut people's access off, stuff like that.

00:40:57.840 --> 00:41:02.879
But after we bought that system and started putting it together, so we could have basically

00:41:02.879 --> 00:41:08.000
built this remote environment with a number of open source tools. We could have used the

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:13.280
open source RStudio. We could have used just a server with a terminal. There's

00:41:13.280 --> 00:41:17.439
tons of different ways we could have done this that would have been cheaper in the short term

00:41:18.159 --> 00:41:24.479
for it. But basically, after we bought RStudio Server, they keep working on it,

00:41:25.040 --> 00:41:31.360
and it kept getting better. So a lot of these things that when we were first

00:41:31.360 --> 00:41:35.439
thinking about it were either not at all security requirements or were things that were on our

00:41:35.439 --> 00:41:41.600
nice-to-have list. At some point in our growth, maybe we were selling

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:46.080
something to a client, they would have some questions about how is your data science

00:41:46.080 --> 00:41:51.919
environment authenticated? And it would be something where I was like,

00:41:51.919 --> 00:41:56.800
if you're authenticating in way A, we're not interested if you're authenticating in way B,

00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:03.679
that'll pass our audit of your work. And so there were many times where basically,

00:42:03.679 --> 00:42:08.159
because we had bought the system and basically just kept getting these patches and updates every

00:42:08.159 --> 00:42:12.800
time we just did the little, there's a new release, let's just spend two minutes

00:42:12.800 --> 00:42:18.159
pseudo-installing the new release. We got those things. They weren't free,

00:42:18.159 --> 00:42:22.159
but they didn't require any work. We didn't have to do some urgent sprint to get those out of the

00:42:22.159 --> 00:42:30.800
box. The thing had kept accumulating features over time. And we've sold product

00:42:30.800 --> 00:42:36.639
based on that. So it's something where I think this is something that's really underrated about

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:43.120
buying software. It's just that you shouldn't think of it in terms of building a short-term

00:42:43.120 --> 00:42:46.879
thing and whether it's more or less expensive to buy or build. You should think about it like,

00:42:47.280 --> 00:42:55.040
how do we want to spend the money and commit the people to maintain the system that we build

00:42:55.040 --> 00:43:00.320
forever? Or do we want to pay somebody else to maintain the system that we do forever?

00:43:00.959 --> 00:43:06.560
And I think unless your business, unless the thing is actually really, really core to your

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:11.439
company, like you're the best in the world at that thing, usually you should try hard to buy things.

00:43:12.399 --> 00:43:17.040
And then the other one is that in addition to this, going back to that kind of developer

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:24.000
experience stuff, that they're also adding developer experience things all the time as

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:29.040
well. This isn't true. This is an RStudio hosted event. So that's part of why I'm talking about

00:43:29.040 --> 00:43:34.239
these RStudio things. But I think this is true of really any vendor that you're doing. Usually,

00:43:34.239 --> 00:43:40.479
if you trust that vendor, they're going to have more skilled people working on this problem than

00:43:40.479 --> 00:43:45.120
you have in-house. So the product that you're going to get out of that is better. An example

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:53.600
here is that we moved several teams to be Python teams at Socure for a variety of hiring reasons.

00:43:55.439 --> 00:43:59.760
And that was something, again, we kind of just had out of the box. We didn't need to.

00:44:00.800 --> 00:44:04.239
Like it wasn't part of our initial purchasing decision really at all, but it was something

00:44:04.239 --> 00:44:12.399
that we were able to add. And then that meant that we could just save a lot of development work,

00:44:12.399 --> 00:44:17.600
but also kind of like centralize access to some of these things where it's like, you're like,

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:21.679
OK, this is the world that we're working on. We want kind of everybody to adhere by these things.

00:44:21.679 --> 00:44:25.520
And we have some examples where at least for many different groups of people, it was successful.

00:44:28.479 --> 00:44:31.919
So those are my three principles. So basically, my advice for this,

00:44:31.919 --> 00:44:35.040
and this is, again, like there's not very much here about like you need to have this

00:44:35.760 --> 00:44:39.600
technical setup. I can answer questions about that if it's helpful, although I think probably

00:44:39.600 --> 00:44:43.280
there are usually better people to answer that. But I do think that this is kind of like an

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:50.719
organizational social thing to a lot of degrees. So like work hard at like developing a relationship

00:44:50.719 --> 00:44:56.239
with your security teams where you all feel like you're on the same team. Try to set up childproof

00:44:56.239 --> 00:45:02.239
environments or maybe like data science proof environments or whatever. Think about developer

00:45:02.239 --> 00:45:07.040
experience as a security problem. Like if they're not at odds with each other, it's not like pick

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:11.120
security or convenience. Like you actually need your secure systems to be convenient for them to

00:45:11.120 --> 00:45:17.520
be successful. And then last, like try hard to buy things. And there are good economic reasons

00:45:17.520 --> 00:45:24.159
why the one you buy is going to be better than the one you build. And then lastly, we are hiring in

00:45:24.239 --> 00:45:31.439
huge numbers. We have a lot of people who are dedicated to our developers as well as many

00:45:31.439 --> 00:45:37.280
dedicated Python developers and some people who do both. So if you would like to hear more about

00:45:37.280 --> 00:45:44.080
this, if fraud is an area that you're interested in, please feel free to reach out. My information

00:45:44.080 --> 00:45:51.360
is here. I'm also on the LinkedIn group. Thank you very much. Thank you so much, Gordon. That

00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:57.199
was awesome. I feel like that is so valuable for so many different industries right now. I'm

00:45:57.199 --> 00:46:01.600
thinking of a lot of conversations I've had with customers in the past who are kind of

00:46:02.239 --> 00:46:08.159
like selling even the idea of data science internally to their teams, where those points

00:46:08.159 --> 00:46:15.840
are really relevant there. Just a reminder, if people have questions, you can use the Zoom chat

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:21.919
here as well. But there's also a Slido link where you can ask anonymous questions. And Gordon, one

00:46:21.919 --> 00:46:32.719
that has been upvoted is, how did you communicate R packages to your security team? Oh, you might

00:46:32.719 --> 00:46:47.120
be muted. So like what an R package is, or you mean like external R packages?

00:46:47.919 --> 00:46:54.320
Probably external ones. Yeah, I think it's just probably coming. I've heard this from a few

00:46:54.320 --> 00:47:01.919
different teams before as well. But if someone doesn't know really what R is, how do you explain

00:47:01.919 --> 00:47:08.000
the idea of packages? Yeah, so I mean, I think like packages are like you could sort of think

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:15.439
about it like, I mean, JavaScript libraries are the same. So the way I sort of think about it

00:47:15.439 --> 00:47:21.120
from a security perspective, and this is kind of like another way where having a robust like

00:47:21.120 --> 00:47:28.560
internal package is really helpful. Because like, I feel like I'm able to make decisions about

00:47:28.800 --> 00:47:35.840
whether a package should be included in our work in a way that other data scientists are not,

00:47:35.840 --> 00:47:39.679
because I've sort of done a fair amount of just like package development. So I kind of know,

00:47:39.679 --> 00:47:43.439
I can look at packages and be like, how good is this package? Like how solid is its development?

00:47:44.159 --> 00:47:48.399
Or like, who developed it, right? Like, so if you're like, I'm much more likely to trust packages

00:47:48.399 --> 00:47:54.560
that are maintained by, you know, a professional, like somebody whose job it is to maintain that,

00:47:55.520 --> 00:47:59.199
and one that's that's ad hoc, I'm much more likely to trust ones that are popular than ones

00:47:59.199 --> 00:48:05.040
that aren't. So if you're kind of like exposing, like have an internal package that you're working

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:09.120
on, that like does almost everything that people need it to do, you'll be able to make that

00:48:09.120 --> 00:48:13.760
decision of just like, I'm not going to take on that dependency. I'm going to do that in

00:48:13.760 --> 00:48:21.280
base R, you do the packages that I already use. And so that's one piece of it. The other piece

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:28.399
is just of like, this is kind of like articulating a threat model as part of that, where you're

00:48:28.399 --> 00:48:34.560
just basically like, like, I think sometimes security people will worry more about an R

00:48:34.560 --> 00:48:39.760
package than they will worry about a JavaScript library, even though the JavaScript library is

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:44.560
probably going to be hacked before the R one is, just because of surface area, like there's more,

00:48:45.120 --> 00:48:48.959
more JavaScript people out there. And actually, like for putting something on NPM or something

00:48:48.959 --> 00:48:56.879
like that, like the, the requirements of doing that are much lower than, than releasing something

00:48:56.879 --> 00:49:02.479
to CRAN. Not that CRAN is not a security thing at all. But, but, but just that there are these

00:49:02.479 --> 00:49:09.120
other places where we inject dependencies all the time. And so I would say like the main thing I

00:49:09.120 --> 00:49:15.280
would sort of argue for there is like to try to get kind of like a fair assessment. Like how is

00:49:15.280 --> 00:49:19.760
it that you use, how is it that we monitor whether somebody is using the right NPM packages or not?

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:23.679
Like, how do we, how do we know that those aren't malicious? Okay. Like we'll do the same thing.

00:49:24.560 --> 00:49:29.520
But, but, but we, but if you don't, if you kind of don't get them to actually articulate what you're

00:49:29.520 --> 00:49:35.360
worried about, you know, like, is it like, is it name, like there's something called name squatting,

00:49:35.360 --> 00:49:40.800
which have, there's a big Python. It wasn't an attack, but it was a thing where you like have

00:49:41.360 --> 00:49:45.919
a Python package that is like, if you just release a new version of the Python package,

00:49:46.639 --> 00:49:51.840
you'll install that one, even if it's malicious. So, so there's sort of like name squatting,

00:49:51.840 --> 00:49:56.080
like there's various different types of ways that like installing an external library can be

00:49:56.080 --> 00:50:01.600
dangerous, but just writing down like what particular ways are we worried about? And then

00:50:01.600 --> 00:50:05.280
figuring out how your thing matches or doesn't match. And there's a lot of different ways you

00:50:05.280 --> 00:50:10.639
can do that. Like having a internal, like air-gapped package repository, a lot of different

00:50:10.639 --> 00:50:15.199
ways you can do that. But, but you just kind of want to make sure that you're not doing this thing

00:50:15.199 --> 00:50:19.520
where it's like, because it's like a language that you don't relate with all the, like, it's

00:50:19.520 --> 00:50:24.399
impossible for people to imagine building a web application without NPM. Right. So that's the same

00:50:24.399 --> 00:50:28.639
for R, right. So I'd say finding like that analogy of just like what these things are and how they

00:50:28.639 --> 00:50:39.360
work is helpful. Thank you. I see there's one other question on Slido that was anonymous. How

00:50:39.360 --> 00:50:44.639
do you deal with a security team that has less knowledge on best practice than the data science

00:50:44.639 --> 00:50:49.919
team? Like the security, probably, like the security side, like if you're having something

00:50:49.919 --> 00:50:57.679
where the, you don't trust your security engineers to have super good ideas. I haven't ever been in

00:50:57.679 --> 00:51:05.360
that situation. So I don't know. The security people, especially at Secure, are very, very good.

00:51:06.560 --> 00:51:16.159
But I would say that, like, you have to meet people where they're at, right. And people have

00:51:16.159 --> 00:51:21.280
power within organizations and you just have to deal with that power. So I think it's,

00:51:21.439 --> 00:51:27.040
so I think, like, not getting frustrated, right, and not, like, as soon as you start talking to

00:51:27.040 --> 00:51:33.600
somebody who has power over a system, as though they're an idiot, right, you've lost, you're done,

00:51:33.600 --> 00:51:40.479
right, you're not going to make any progress with that. So you need to, like, look at their sort of

00:51:40.479 --> 00:51:45.280
work, look at their stuff, and try to understand it in a sympathetic way, right. And one of the

00:51:45.280 --> 00:51:49.600
tools that I do a lot is I kind of like, you know, like repeating the same thing over and over,

00:51:50.399 --> 00:51:53.919
you know, like repeating things back to people is helpful to just be like, okay,

00:51:53.919 --> 00:51:58.000
what's the most charitable way that I can say back to you my understanding of this.

00:51:59.439 --> 00:52:04.239
And then, like, you can sort of take that and sort of, like, write down, like, okay, here's,

00:52:04.239 --> 00:52:07.840
here's what we wrote down as, like, this is that requirement, this is why we have it,

00:52:08.479 --> 00:52:13.360
right, this is the motivation for it, get kind of broad agreement on that. And then sort of,

00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:18.639
like, move forward, right, you're like, this, given that this kind of, like, fulfills those

00:52:18.639 --> 00:52:26.800
things. But yeah, like, you can't, you can't treat people like, like, they're, they're dumb.

00:52:27.439 --> 00:52:31.520
Because, because it just, that's, that's, again, kind of that bad place where you're, you're,

00:52:33.280 --> 00:52:37.199
like, you're not, like, as soon as people stop trusting each other, like, you're going to ask

00:52:37.199 --> 00:52:39.919
for something that's totally reasonable in six months, and they're just going to say,

00:52:40.719 --> 00:52:44.639
man, like, that jerk, I'm gonna say no right away, right? There's a lot of discretion in

00:52:44.639 --> 00:52:48.479
these things. And I guess the thing I did have experience with that is, like, dealing with,

00:52:48.479 --> 00:52:52.080
I used to be a lawyer, and I used to deal with, like, administrator, like, government administrators.

00:52:53.679 --> 00:52:57.439
And that's kind of like a similar thing, where you're like, oh, man, this is, it's so stupid,

00:52:57.439 --> 00:53:02.159
I have to file this in triplicate. But if I make a big fuss about filing it in triplicate, I'm gonna

00:53:02.159 --> 00:53:06.479
have to do three other things. So, like, so you want to kind of, like, try to build that

00:53:06.479 --> 00:53:10.239
relationship. And then over time, if you do have that relationship, it's easier to kind of, like,

00:53:10.239 --> 00:53:13.600
educate and bring in other resources about how to do it.

00:53:15.679 --> 00:53:20.320
Thank you. I think that's such a good lesson in communication, in general, and, like, thinking

00:53:20.320 --> 00:53:26.320
about, like, even when you're sharing visualizations with, like, people from the business as well.

